        <h1 class="max-w-3xl font-display font-bold text-3xl sm:text-4xl text-slate-100 leading-tight tracking-tight mb-6">
          Read-Only MCP Removes a Failure Class, But Only if the Whole Tool Boundary Is Actually Read-Only
        </h1>
        <p class="max-w-3xl text-lg text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
          Read-only MCP matters because it can remove an entire mutation failure class. But the claim only holds when the surrounding runtime preserves a real inspect-only boundary instead of leaving write-capable side doors open.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 pt-10 pb-24">
      <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-4 mb-10">
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-emerald-500/20 bg-emerald-500/5 p-4">
          <div class="text-[11px] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-emerald-400 mb-2">Inspect</div>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">Read and observe without mutation. The cleanest trust class to hand an agent early.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-amber/20 bg-amber/5 p-4">
          <div class="text-[11px] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-amber mb-2">Write</div>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">Changes data or configuration. Should stay visibly separate from inspect-only surfaces.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-rose-500/20 bg-rose-500/5 p-4">
          <div class="text-[11px] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-rose-400 mb-2">Execute</div>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">Triggers side effects that may be indirect, broad, or hard to reverse.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-sky-500/20 bg-sky-500/5 p-4">
          <div class="text-[11px] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-sky-400 mb-2">Egress</div>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">Sends information or outputs elsewhere. Often the forgotten side door in “read-only” claims.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-[28px] border border-slate-800 bg-surface/80 p-6 mb-10">
        <div class="text-[11px] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.24em] text-slate-500 mb-3">The real test</div>
        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed text-lg">
          The useful question is not <span class="text-slate-100">“Does this MCP server expose only read calls?”</span>
          It is <span class="text-slate-100">“Does the surrounding runtime preserve a real read-only trust class across the whole tool boundary?”</span>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <div class="max-w-none" set:html={ARTICLE_HTML} />

        <div class="mt-12 rounded-[28px] border border-sky-500/20 bg-sky-500/5 p-6">
          <div class="text-[11px] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.24em] text-sky-300 mb-3">Schema and output legibility</div>
          <h2 class="font-display font-semibold text-2xl text-slate-100 tracking-tight mb-3">
            A read-only tool can still leak the wrong world if its output is too broad.
          </h2>
          <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The fresh official-server signal is a useful stress test: a helper that returns the full environment may look inspect-only, but broad environment disclosure turns read authority into secret and topology exposure. The boundary should specify which keys, prefixes, paths, or metadata classes are safe to return before the model ever sees the blob.
          </p>
          <p class="text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            The same applies to underspecified schemas. If filesystem or environment parameters have weak descriptions, the model cannot tell safe inspection from authority probing. Read-only trust needs narrow output shape plus machine-legible parameter descriptions, not just an absence of write verbs.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-12 rounded-[28px] border border-violet-500/20 bg-violet-500/5 p-6">
          <div class="text-[11px] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.24em] text-violet-300 mb-3">Pricing boundary</div>
          <h2 class="font-display font-semibold text-2xl text-slate-100 tracking-tight mb-3">
            Read-only proof is free until the workflow earns a write lane
          </h2>
          <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-5">
            A read-only surface is evidence about what cannot happen. Rhumb should not price inspection, denied escalation, or schema proof as execution; it should price the later governed lane only when the operator deliberately opens one bounded write, execute, or egress path.
          </p>
          <div class="grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-3">
            {PRICING_BOUNDARY_CHECKS.map((item) => (
              <div class="rounded-2xl border border-violet-500/20 bg-navy/60 p-4 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-300">{item}</div>
            ))}
          </div>
          <p class="mt-5 text-sm text-slate-500">
            Pricing proof: <a href="/pricing?rhumb_experiment=e006&rhumb_source=read-only-pricing-boundary" class="text-amber hover:text-amber-200 transition-colors">see the MCP discovery pricing boundary</a>
            <span class="mx-2 text-slate-700">/</span>
            Execution preflight: <a href="/start-managed-execution?rhumb_experiment=e006&rhumb_source=read-only-pricing-boundary" class="text-amber hover:text-amber-200 transition-colors">scope managed execution</a>
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-12 rounded-[28px] border border-emerald-500/20 bg-emerald-500/5 p-6">
          <div class="text-[11px] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.24em] text-emerald-300 mb-3">Next honest step</div>
          <h2 class="font-display font-semibold text-2xl text-slate-100 tracking-tight mb-3">
            Use inspect-only as the first trust class, then open one bounded execution lane
          </h2>
          <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-5">
            If the agent has proven it can inspect safely and the workflow now needs repeatable writes,
            do not jump straight to a connector graveyard. Start with one governed lane, then widen authority
            only when the job earns it.
          </p>
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-3">
            <a href="/blog/capability-first-agent-onboarding?rhumb_experiment=e004&rhumb_source=read-only-trust-onboarding" class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-xl bg-emerald-400 px-5 py-3 text-sm font-display font-semibold text-navy hover:bg-emerald-300 transition-colors duration-200">
              See the capability-first handoff →
            </a>
